for the sustainable shared management of water resources that is presented in Water Wisdom. Their essays explore the full range of scientific, political, social, and economic issues related to water use in the region; acknowledge areas of continuing controversy, from access rights to the Mountain Aquifer to utilization of waters from the Jordan River; and identify areas of agreement, disagreement, and options for resolution. Water Wisdom is model for those who believe that water conflict can be an opportunity for cooperation rather than violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWater resources developmentxEnvironmental aspectszMiddle East. 0aWater resources developmentxGovernment policyzMiddle East. 0aWater resources developmentzMiddle EastxPlanning. 0aWater-supplyzMiddle EastxInternational cooperation. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbdeen, Ziad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbdeen, Ziad.1 aAbu-Mayla, Yousef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbu-Mayla, Yousef.1 aAburdeineh, Iyad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAburdeineh, Iyad.1 aAdar, Eilon M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdar, Eilon.1 aAliewi, Amjad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAliewi, Amjad.1 aAssaf, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssaf, Karen.1 aAssaf, Said A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssaf, Said.1 aAvisar, Dror, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvisar, Dror.1 aBen-Gal, Alon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Gal, Alon.1 aBromberg, Gidon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu